6  a  b Materials and methods Public datasets downloading and processing We downloaded whole-genome sequencing (WGS) datasets from three publicly available sources ( Table S1 https://github.com/samtools/samtools 24 25 et al 12 Downsampling procedures We downsampled the dWGS data to mimic real-world lcWGS depths using Picard with the Chained strategy. The sampling probability was calculated by dividing the original average sequencing depth (computed using Samtools) by the target depth. For each target depth, we generated 10 technical replicates using distinct random seeds (1–10). The performance of downsampling methods was evaluated by comparing the CNV detected from simulated data against the ground truth. We benchmarked three methods: Picard’s ( http://broadinstitute.github.io/picard/ Fig. S1 Copy number variation detection We benchmarked five CNV detection tools: ACE [ 20 21 22 23 Table 1 26 Table S2 Runtime performance was evaluated using the GNU time command (bash version 5.1.16). All benchmarks were executed on a Ubuntu Linux 22.04.5 LTS system equipped with Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8375C CPU processors (physical cores: 64, logical processors: 128) operating at 2.90 GHz base frequency. Evaluation of copy number variation detection tools using the NA12878 copy number variation set as the standard set The third-generation sequencing (TGS) dataset contained a total of 20 120 CNVs, comprising 12 535 amplifications and 7585 deletions, with a median length of 106 bp (range: 1–5 686 936 bp). To enable comparative analysis between TGS data and simulated low-coverage WGS (lcWGS) data (median length = 2 238 502 bp, range: 10 001–249 230 622 bp), we implemented a multi-step processing pipeline for the TGS-derived CNVs. First, we filtered out all CNVs shorter than 1000 bp. Next, the remaining 1285 CNVs were consolidated using the bt.merge function in the R package bedtoolsr 27 To evaluate the performance of CNV detection tools, we calculated the precision, recall, and F1 