ection. Five CNV detection tools were applied. We evaluated the performance in terms of profile match score, number of CNVs, length of segments, and cytoband patterns. Step 3: Copy number feature extraction. Three copy number signature analysis methods were used in detected CNV datasets, and the stability of features were evaluated with feature similarity. The complete analytical framework is systematically depicted in Fig. 1 Materials and Methods Figure 1 Study design. Our experimental design systematically assesses five critical dimensions: (1) biospecimen type, (2) sequencing center variability, (3) tumor purity, (4) sequencing depth variability, and (5) analytical pipelines for CNV detection and signature analysis. The framework integrates in silico simulations with real-world genomic data to benchmark performance across conditions. Performance was benchmarked using five complementary metrics. Schematic diagram of the experimental study design. Performance evaluation for copy number variation detection tools on NA12878 simulated datasets across varying sequencing depths We generated a simulated dataset at 0.1×, 0.2×, 0.5×, and 1×–10× depth for NA12878, and then five CNV detection tools were applied. To precisely compare the performance of these tools, we used a CNV dataset obtained from third-generation sequencing as the gold standard. The CNVs detected at different sequencing depths were compared with this gold standard to calculate precision, recall, and F1 score (details in Materials and Methods Fig. 2a Fig. 2b Figure 2 Performance evaluation for CNV detection tools on NA12878 simulated datasets across varying sequencing depths. (a) Precision, recall, and F1 score across sequencing depths ranging from 0.1× to 10×. (b) Number of amplified and deleted CNVs. The gray dashed line indicates the gold-standard reference of 102 CNVs, which are all deletions. (c) Arm-level patterns across different CNV calling methods at the same downsampling simulation depth (2× depth). (d) Computational runtime curves under varying sequencing depths. Four-part figure evaluating CNV detection tools: (a) Line charts (5 panels) showing precision, recall, and F1 scores (3 lines each) across 0.1 ×–10× depths. (b) Bar charts (5 panels) displaying amplified/deleted CNV counts (y-axis) with gray reference line (102 deletions) across depths (x-axis). (c) Chromosome arm grid with rows (tools), columns (arms), and color-coded copy number states (red = amplification, white = neutral, blue = deletion). (d) Line charts (5 panels) of computational runtime (y-axis) across depths (x-axis). We conducted a comparison of detected CNV numbers across different sequencing depths ( Fig. 2b We further performed arm-level comparisons between the gold-standard CNV and results from the five tools ( Fig. 2c Fig. 2d Impact of formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded fixation time on copy number variation detection To investigate the impact of FFPE fixation time on CNV detection, we analyzed samples subjected to FFPE for 1, 2, 6, and 24 h, using matched fresh-frozen samples from the same sequencing center (Illumina HiSeq) as ground truth. All specimens were downsampled to 2× depth (mean of original depth = 64.34×) to simulate low-coverage sequencing scenarios. The total CNV number showed a time-dependent escalation (except CNVs detected by ASCAT.sc), with 24-h-processed specimens exhibiting 26% more events than 1-h counterparts ( P Fig. 3a Fig. 3b P Figure 3 Impact of FFPE fixation time on CNV detection performance under low-coverage sequencing. N P * P * * P * * * P * * * * P Two-part analysis of FFPE fixation time effects: (a) Box plots (5 panels) showing CNV counts (y-axis) across fixation times (x-axis). (b) Violin plots (5 panels) displaying segment length distributions (y-axis) across fixation times (x-axis), with violin width representing segment abundance. Impact of tumor purity on copy number variation detection To evaluate the performance of CNV detection tools under varying tumor purities, we analyzed artificial mixtures of HCC1395 (breast cancer cell line) and HCC1395BL (normal B lymphocyte cell line) at defined ratios (75%, 50%, 20%, 10%, and 5% tumor fraction). All specimens were downsampled to 2× depth (mean original depth = 90×) using matched high-purity (100%) dWGS samples as ground truth. At low purity (<50%), CNVkit demonstrated superior correction capability, effectively mitigating normal cell contamination effects ( Fig. 4a Fig. 4a Fig. 4b c Figure 4 Impact of tumor purity on CNV detection performance under low-coverage sequencing. N * P * * P * * * P * * * * P Three-panel tumor purity impact analysis: (a) Box plots (5 panels) showing copy number profile match scores (y-axis) across tumor purity levels (y-axis: 5%–100%). (b) Box plots (5 panels) displaying CNV counts (y-axis) across tumor purity levels (x-axis). (c) Violin plots (5 panels) illustrating segment length distributions (y-axis) across purity levels (x-axis). Impact of sequencing center variability on copy number variation detection To assess intercenter reproducibility, we analyzed data from seven distinct sequencing centers. The original sequencing data (mean depth = 54.11×) was downsampled to 2× for simulating low-coverage sequencing conditions. Pairwise comparisons of CNV profiles across centers ( Fig. 5a Fig. 5a Fig. 5b Fig. 5c Figure 5 Impact of sequencing center variability on CNV detection performance under low-coverage sequencing. N et al * P * * P * * * P * * * * P Three-part sequencing center variability analysis: (a) Nested heatmaps: 5 × 5 tool-grid containing 7 × 7 center-pair grids with profile match scores. (b) Box plots (5 panels) of CNV counts (y-axis) across centers (x-axis). (c) Violin plots (5 panels) of segment length distributions (y-axis) across centers (x-axis). Cross-condition correlation analysis of copy number features Copy number signatures represent recurrent patterns of somatic copy number alterations, which provide novel perspectives for the study of tumorigenesis. Copy number signatures are derived from mathematical decomposition of copy number features (e.g. segment size/breakpoint density). Here, we compared three distinct copy number signature analysis methods—the Steele et al 17 et al 16 et al 18 et al et al et al Evaluating signature stability across sequencing depths using HCC1395 samples (simulated depths: 0.5 ×–10× versus original 91.94×) revealed tool-specific patterns ( Fig. 6a Figure 6 Cosine similarity of copy number features cross conditions. (a) Copy number features of HCC1395, comparing simulated datasets against the real-world dataset (91.94× depth). (b) Copy number features of HCC1395, comparing FFPE-fixed samples against the fresh specimen. N = 10 technical replicates per fixation time. (c) Copy number features of HCC1395, comparing samples of different tumor purity levels against the pure tumor sample. N = 10 technical replicates per purity level. (Continued on next page). (d) Copy number features of HCC1395, pairwise comparisons across seven sequencing centers. Heat map displays feature similarity scores between pairs of sequencing centers analyzed with specified CNV-calling tools corresponding to the row and column. Statistical annotation: ns = not significant ( P * P * * P * * * P * * * * P Four-part cosine similarity analysis: (a) Bar charts (5 panels) of similarity (y-axis) across sequencing depths (x-axis) per tool. (b) Box plot matrix (3 × 5: methods × tools) of similarity (y-axis) across FFPE fixation time (x-axis). (c) Box plot matrix (3 × 5: methods × tools) of similarity (y-axis) across tumor purity (x-axis). (d) Nested heatmaps: 5 × 5 tool-grid with 7 × 7 center-pair grids. In comparative analysis of FFPE-processed versus fresh-frozen HCC1395 specimens, most tools showed significant variations across FFPE processing times ( Fig. 6b Fig. 6c Fig. 6d Discussion This comprehensive benchmark study provides critical insights into the performance of CNV detection tools in lcWGS data, establishing evidence-based guidelines for optimizing analytical workflows in research or clinical settings. Our findings highlight four major dimensions of variability: (i) sequencing depth dependency, (ii) technical artifacts from FFPE fixation, (iii) tumor purity, and (iv) algorithmic divergence in CNV calling tools and signature analysis methods. Collectively, these factors shape the reliability of CNV detection and downstream signature analysis. The marked superiority of ichorCNA in balancing precision and recall, even at ultra-low depths (0.5 ×–1×) aligns with its superior noise tolerance, as its original application to circulating tumor DNA analysis [ 23 Fig. 2d 19 21 22 7 8 Fig. 5a Our comparative analysis of sequencing depth revealed that the F1 score of CNV detection stabilized at depths ≥3× ( Fig. 2a Fig. 2b Formaldehyde induces DNA crosslinks, fragmentation, and base modifications [ 29 et al 30 et al 31 Fig. 3b 32 At the signature level, global statistical features derived from the Wang method (such as BP10Mb and BoChr) exhibited superior cross-condition stability. Specifically, components including BP10Mb (genome-wide breakpoint density per 10 Mb) and BoChr (chromosomal copy number burden) robustly integrated chromosomal/arm-level variation information, significantly reducing sensitivity to local technical noise ( Fig. S2 Below, we provide condition-specific technical recommendations informed by our systematic benchmarking:  Tool priority:  Signature analysis method selection:  Depth requirements:  FFPE limitations:  Tumor purity requirements:  Multi-center comparability: While we employed third-generation sequencing of NA12878 as a gold-standard reference, its inherent limitations in resolving complex structural variations may compromise the accurate representation of true copy number landscapes. Direct simulation of WGS data—where ground-truth CNVs are predefined—could enable more rigorous benchmarking of tool performance in discriminating deletions versus amplifications and detecting segments across distinct size thresholds. Additionally, real-world clinical specimens often exhibit higher genomic heterogeneity. Future studies should validate these findings in multi-region tumor sequencing datasets. In conclusion, this study establishes that lcWGS can reliably capture biologically informative CNV patterns when analytical workflows are rigorously optimized for depth, specimen type, tumor purity, and tool selection. By mapping the boundaries of technical feasibility, we provide a roadmap for implementing cost-effective copy number profiling in precisiononcology. Key Points We benchmarked five CNV detection tools using lcWGS datasets, evaluating performance across sequencing depth, FFPE artifacts, multi-center reproducibility, and signature stability. ichorCNA outperformed all tools in precision, recall, and runtime, achieving optimal F1 scores even at ultra-low depths (≥0.5×). FFPE fixation induces artifactual short-segment CNVs, a bias no tool could computationally correct, necessitating strict fixation control or fresh-frozen samples. Tumor purity critically modulates accuracy of CNV calling: CNVkit shows good correction ability at low purity (<50%), while ichorCNA requires higher (≥50%) purity for optimal performance. The Wang method for copy number signature extraction showed superior cross-condition stability versus Steele or Tao methods. Supplementary Material fig_S1_bbaf514 fig_S2_bbaf514 Table_S1_bbaf514 Table_S2_bbaf514 Acknowledgements We thank the ShanghaiTech University High Performance Computing Public Service Platform for computing services. We thank the multi-omics facility, molecular and cell biology core facility of ShanghaiTech University for technical help. We thank Raymond Shuter for editing the text. Author contributions N.W. and Z.T. collected data, performed computational analysis and wrote the manuscript. T.W., J.W., W.W., and H.S. participated in critical project discussi